{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"84459d6e-72b3-432c-9385-6a7eabb300da","content":"Here are the evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading file contents via property functions executes during evaluation — blocking and expensive. Move this to a target that runs at build time, or use a task like `ReadLinesFromFile`.\n\n## 2. Broad Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. As the repo grows (especially if `node_modules`, `.git`, or other large directories appear), this becomes progressively slower. Narrow the glob or add exclusions via `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n## 3. Deep Import Chain (Low Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree nested imports is mild, but this pattern scales poorly. Each import adds an evaluation pass. Prefer flatter structures (e.g., `Directory.Build.props`) for shared settings.\n\n---\n\n**Priority fix:** Remove the `System.IO.File::ReadAllText` call — it's the costliest pattern here since it performs synchronous disk I/O on every evaluation (IDE background evaluations included).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"96bd4674-2fec-4aec-aacd-44e3c312a1b3","outputTokens":359,"requestId":"7C15:6928E:C0DD9A:DCEC0C:6A02802A"},"id":"16b60d8e-0a2b-4f4b-9562-cb6b8885ee3e","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:19:50.398Z","parentId":"d5772a4d-244a-4473-b36f-19d8244f4c75"}
